description.plain:
“Wish on an Eyelash” is the opening track on Australian singer-songwriter Mallrat’s debut album Butterfly Blue. Its lyrics sing about someone wishing to be with their lover.

The song would later be extended and remixed by The Chainsmokers. This version was released as “Wish On An Eyelash, Pt. 2”.

description.plain: The song started in a Chainsmokers european tour which, while turisting in Prague, the original Wish On An Eyelash song by Mallrat popped on Drew Taggart’s playlist. He found the original track too short so he decided to make it longer, after that, on November 19th, Chainsmokers posted a short video with the new version on Instagram tagging Mallrat. Both, Mallrat and Chainsmokers fans, started to ask for the full release and the song was released on December 9th with the title “Wish On An Eyelash, Pt.2”.

annotations: Made a wish on elevens
Making a wish on elevens refers to 11:11 when people commonly make a wish. This is called an “angel number” and is said to be when your angel is closest to you, so your wish may be granted.
I made a wish on an eyelash

Making a wish on a fallen eyelash is an old folklore gesture. Wishers would place the fallen eyelash on the back of their hand before throwing it over their shoulder as they imagined what they wanted.

In this case that wish is for the speakers love and for them to be together

When we leave all the parties
 When we’re not in our bodies
 When we’re up in a spaceship
 That’s when I feel the greatest

The speaker expresses how much they love spending time with this person, especially when they are alone “leaving the party”

The reference to being out of body can be taken two different ways
1. Meaning an intense feeling of how they feel when alone with this person
2. What they feel when they are in a high or drunk state with the other person
I’ve been tryin’ to tell ya
The speaker has to get something off their chest, particularly to a person who they have kept their feelings a secret from but can’t hide them any longer

description.plain:
“Groceries” is the opening track on Mallrat’s In the Sky EP. The track was first previewed on Beats 1 by Zane Lowe and has been described as having a “strumming guitar melody that shines amongst her vocals”.

Mallrat describes the track as:

It’s about having a crush but not wanting to have a crush on someone. Being like, this is so annoying, I don’t want this. I love being independent, so when you really like someone it can be annoying.

“Groceries” became the most succesful track in Mallrat’s career at the time, being featured on Billboard’s “Best Songs of 2018: Critics Picks” and was the #7 in the 2019 Hottest 100.

Something as task-like and mundane as getting groceries in most situations would be seen as boring, or mundane. But mundane can be personal. But in Mallrat’s head it’s an invitation to be emotionally intimate with her uninterested crush. Something that people do everyday being turned to something so thrilling and personal.

Notably the chorus is the only part where Mallrat truly gives into her feelings, moving past the overall theme of this crush being an emotional annoyance.

No one I know is sticking on my mind when I go

Mallrat has no interest in anyone but her crush, but he only sees her as a friend, an independent woman whom he cannot see being in a relationship.

This is a reference to one of two songs: “Miss Independent” by Kelly Clarkson from her debut album Thankful, or “Miss Independent” by Ne-Yo from his album Year of the Gentlemen.

Charlie is about a lot of different things but mostly just loving people so much, regardless of whether it’s reciprocated or not.

annotations:
I just want coffee for breakfast
 I just want warm cups of tea
 I just might love you forever

Love as a simple and straightforward act is a theme for Mallrat. As in her song Groceries, her desires are as simple as getting food with her lover: just coffee, just warm cups of tea, and just loving them forever.

She says that love is like a chess game
 And boys gotta do the chasing
 But when did I start taking her advice?
 I raised myself and that’s alright
This is the advice from Mallrat’s mother. Mallrat acknowledges the fact she raised herself and is okay with that but won’t start taking her mums advice

I want coffee for breakfast
 I want warm cups of tea
 I’m gonna love you forever
 I hope you warm up to me

The motif of warmth is present throughout the song. In the chorus, Mallrat first mentions coffee and tea, warm drinks, saying that she wants the warmth of her lover in her life. Then she says she hopes her lover “warms up” to her. Finally, in verse 3, she mentions “ice melting when winter turns to spring”, something that happens due to warmth. Through the entire song, she compares her lover to warmth and springtime.
I hope you warm up to me

This can be linked to how the song is based around the love for a new pet; “warming up” is something a lot of pets do when meeting their new owner. It also can be interpreted in romantic love with a partner and getting used to a new relationship, backing up the sort of double meaning this song has with platonic/romantic relationships.

All you gotta do is wait for me to get home
 Like Charlie in the rain outside
 All I wanna do is see you when I get home
 Like Charlie in the rain outside
 All you gotta do is wait for me to get home
 Like Charlie in the rain outside
 All I wanna do is see you when I get home
 Like Charlie in the rain outside

“Charlie” is the name of the singer’s golden retriever, which are dogs known for being hard-working and obedient, (many serve as service dogs, or dogs trained to help people with a disability). The singer’s own dog is also very loyal, and will wait for her in the rain when she comes back home. In the same way, the singer wants to be able to count on another person to love her as unconditionally as her dog loves her.

Said, you can lead a horse to water
 But you can’t always make it drink
She’s willing to confess her feelings towards this other person and acknowledges that he may not reciprocate them, but is okay if that’s the case.
I think about you when I sing

Calls back to her earlier 2019 single with Basenji, “Nobody’s Home,” where she’s daydreaming about a love interest while sitting at home alone; the line goes “Nobody’s home, so I sing my songs about you, and when nobody’s close, I can think a lot about you, boy”
I think you might be my angel

Though still referring to her dog, this line echoes the angel metaphors used in her 2018 song “Better,” off of her EP “In the Sky,” where Mallrat sings “maybe all the angels had to fly” and “now I’ve got an angel in the sky…”

description.plain:
“Surprise Me” is a 2022 single by Mallrat, and marks her first collaboration with American rapper Azealia Banks.

In a press release sent to Paste Magazine, Mallrat said:

It’s so true that the music you listen to when you’re little really shapes you. Or at least it hangs out in your subconscious for a very long time. The first album I ever bought with my own money was Broke With Expensive Taste. She was truly the best to work with. It felt like she really cared, which you don’t always get with feature artists; often, it can feel like they’re fulfilling an obligation. Maybe I’m biased, but hers is one of the most iconic and memorable verses I’ve ever heard.

description.plain: In this dreamy, psychedelic pop-rock track, Mallrat kisses her lover goodbye after recognizing she’s been taken for granted. She lets her now-ex know that she’s onto bigger and better things, whether that’s a future rockstar partner, a sweep of the Grammys, and a happy family. It’s too late for her ex to win her back, even if the heartbreak is visceral to her now.
